{"title": "Everything Has Rhythm", "content": "Just because something is nonliving doesn't mean it can't be part of a song. This trope happens mostly in musicals and operas, when a character interacts with an inanimate object during a musical number. It exists partially to make a scene look more realistic. For instance, which would be more effective: a character who is carrying a broom and instantly stops using it just to sing a song, or a character who is carrying a broom, starts singing and incorporates the broom into the song? Most musicals would choose the latter.\n\nThis trope exists in two forms:\n\u2022 The character uses, say, a broom for its intended purpose, but doing it to the beat or rhythm of the music.\n\u2022 The character dances with or plays with the broom during the song.\n\nNote: This trope incorporates inanimate objects as part of the choreography of a musical number. If a number uses such objects as musical instruments or use them for percussive reasons, it is not this trope, it is an example of Everything Is an Instrument.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/EverythingHasRhythm", "media_links": ["https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/LetMeCallYouSweetheart", "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Music/ElvisPresley", "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Enchanted", "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Theatre/ByeByeBirdie", "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Disney/BeautyAndTheBeast", "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/FredAstaire", "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/GeneKelly", "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/GeneKelly", "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/FredAstaire", "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Hairspray", "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/LittleShopOfHorrors", "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Theatre/TheMusicMan", "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Theatre/OnTheTown", "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php